FUNCEME), Av. Rui Barbosa, 1246 Fortaleza, Ceará, Brazil; Boulanger, J.-P., LOCEAN-IPSL, Institut de Recherche pour le Développement (IRD), UMR 182, UPMC Tour 45-55, 4 place Jussieu case 100, 75252 Paris cedex 05, France","Dengue fever is the most prevalent mosquito-borne viral disease of humans in tropical lands. As an efficient vaccine is not yet available, the only means to prevent epidemics is to control mosquito populations. These are influenced by human behavior and climatic conditions and thus, need constant effort and are very expansive. Examples of succeeded prevention are rare because of the continuous reintroduction of virus or vector from outside, or growing resistance of mosquito populations to insecticides. Climate variability and global warming are other factors which may favour epidemics of dengue. During a pilot study in Claris EC project, a model for the transmission of dengue was built, to serve as a tool for estimating the risk of epidemic transmission and eventually forecasting the risk under climatic change scenarios. An ultimate objective would be to use the model as an early warning system with meteorological forecasts as input, thus allowing better decision making and prevention. © Springer Science + Business Media B.V. 2009.",,"Climate impacts; Climate variability; Climatic changes; Climatic conditions; Early Warning System; Human behaviors; Pilot studies; Tropical lands; Viral disease; Behavioral research; Climatology; Epidemiology; Global warming; Mosquito control; Risk perception; Viruses; Weather forecasting; Pest control; climate effect; climate variation; decision making; dengue fever; disease control; disease transmission; disease vector; epidemic; insecticide; mosquito; public health; risk assessment; vaccine; weather forecasting",,,,,,"Almeida, M.C., Caiaffa, W.T., Assunção, R.M., Proietti, F.A., Spatial vulnerability to dengue in a Brazilian urban area during a 7-year surveillance (2007) J Urban Health: Bull N Y Acad Med, 84, pp. 